      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to question the immediate financial burden, as the reality is that working people will feel the cost before seeing the long-term benefits of reduced traffic and cleaner air. However, framing it as \"equitable\" is only valid if we commit to the political will required to implement those tiered structures and ensure the revenue is legally mandated to fund transit expansion, rather than being lost to administrative bloat. The argument for congestion pricing isn't about ignoring the pain of the transition, but about accepting that the current status quo of gridlock and pollution is a far greater, permanent cost to our society.",
      "source": "target",
